    %section
      %h1 Abstract
      =image_tag "investment_education/TimeValueOfMoney1.png"
      %p 
        In finance, we are concerned with the idea that money has a potential earning capacity. A sum of money at present has a higher value than the same amount of money in the future. For example Rs. 1 received today is worth more than Rs. 1 received one year later. The idea is that if we receive the money today, we could invest it and earn interest on the money. So, one year later, we would have the original Rs. 1 as well as the interest earned on it.
      %p 
        If we were to let the bank hold our money, it is only fair that we receive some interest payments as compensation from the bank because by receiving our money later, we are postponing our consumption to a later period.
    %section
      %h1 Calculating Simple Interest
      %p 
        For a saver, simple interest is earned as a percentage of the original sum, or the principal amount. This interest is paid out at the end of a specific period.
      %p 
        For example, assume that a saver deposits Rs. 1000 into a bank, wishing to only withdraw the money at the end of 5 years. Also assume that the bank promises to pay simple interest of 5% per annum.
      %p 
        In the time line below, each year is denoted by Y0, Y1, Y2, Y3, Y4, Y5. The time today is denoted by Year 0 or Y0. In exactly one year’s time, the time will be denoted by Year 1 or Y1. In two years’ time, the time will denoted by Y2, and so on. The amount of money flowing to the saver at the end of each period is known as the cash flow.
