        %tr
          %th Year
          %th Simple Interest
          %th Total Amount After Year No.
        %tr
          %td Y0
          %td
          %td
        %tr
          %td Y1
          %td 5%X Rs. 1000 = Rs. 50
          %td Rs. 1000+Rs. 50 = Rs. 1050
        %tr
          %td Y2
          %td 5%X Rs. 1000 = Rs. 50
          %td Rs. 1050+Rs. 50 = Rs. 1100
        %tr
          %td Y3
          %td 5%X Rs. 1000 = Rs. 50
          %td Rs. 1100+Rs. 50 = Rs. 1150
        %tr
          %td Y4
          %td 5%X Rs. 1000 = Rs. 50
          %td Rs. 1150+Rs. 50 = Rs. 1200
        %tr
          %td Y5
          %td 5%X Rs. 1000 = Rs. 50
          %td Rs. 1200+Rs. 50 = Rs. 1250
      %p At the end of 5 years, the saver will receive Rs. 1250, consisting of Rs. 1000 in principal sum and Rs. 250 in simple interest. Note that simple interest is calculated as a percentage of Rs. 1000, which is the principal sum.
    %section
      %h1 Calculating Compound Interest
      %p Compound Interest: For a saver, compound interest is earned as a percentage of the total sum of the original principal amount plus any interest earned. This interest is paid out at the end of a specific period.
      %p For example, assume that a saver deposits Rs. 1000 into a bank, wishing to only withdraw the money at the end of 5 years. Also assume that the bank promises to pay a compound interest of 5% per annum compounded annually.
      %p The interest at the end of 1 year is Rs. 50. The principal for the calculation of interest for the 2nd year is the principal at the beginning of the 1st year plus the interest earned for the 1st year i.e. Rs. 1000 + Rs. 50 = Rs. 1050.
