    %section
      %h1 Present Value:
      %p
        The value of money today (or time Y0). In this case, the present value is denoted by CF0. The cash flow for the saver at Y0 should be Rs. 1000 since he is leaving Rs. 1000 with the bank.
        The present value can be defined as the current value of a future amount of money, calculated based a specific interest rate. It can be calculated using the following formula: (FV )/[(1+R)]^t where FV represents the future value and R represents the interest rate.
        That means that a saver earning an interest rate of R % p.a. will be indifferent to receiving Rs. 1 today or Rs. (1+R) one year down the line.
    %section
      %h1 Future Value:
      %p
        The value of money at the end of a specific period. The future value of Rs. 1000 in 5 years time will be CF5, the future value of Rs. 1000 in 4 years’ time will be CF4, and so on. It can also be defined as the value of a present amount
        of money at a particular time in the future, calculated based on a specific interest rate. It can be calculated using the following formula: 〖PV (1+R)〗^t where PV represents the present value and R represents the interest rate.
